Use an [alias][1] for the properties that have a dash `-` :

`atomic-number` is not a [valid variable name][2] in javascript.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const obj = {
      &quot;atomic-number&quot;: 98,
      group: null,
      &quot;molar-mass&quot;: 251,
      name: &quot;Californium&quot;,
      period: 7,
      symbol: &quot;Cf&quot;,
      _id: &quot;5d90ab91d84d48bff5ef7c59&quot;
    };

    const { &quot;atomic-number&quot;: atomicNumber } = obj;

    console.log(atomicNumber);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://davidwalsh.name/destructuring-alias
  [2]: https://mothereff.in/js-variables

Although dashes are valid for json keys (and js obj keys), they are invalid for js variables.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let x = {&quot;a-b&quot;: 3}; // OK

    // let {a-b} = x; // SyntaxError
    // let {&quot;a-b&quot;} = x; // SyntaxError

    let {&quot;a-b&quot;: ab} = x; // OK

    console.log(x);
    console.log(ab);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Well since you can not have `-` in a variable name, you are going to have to alias it. 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var foo = {&#39;atomic-number&#39;: 98 }


    const { &#39;atomic-number&#39;: atomicNumber } = foo

    console.log(atomicNumber)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

